Let's simplify the given equation in the question step by step. 

Given equation: $\quad 3(2x - a) = 2(3x + 12)$

Expanding both sides: \quad \begin{align*}

\implies 3(2x) - 3(a) &= 2(3x) + 2(12)  \\
6x - 3a  &= 6x + 24
\end{align*}

Subtracting $6x$ from both sides: \quad \begin{align*}

\implies -3a  &= 24
\end{align*}

Dividing both sides by $-3$: \quad \begin{align*}

\implies a  &= \dfrac {24}{-3}
\end{align*}

Simplifying: \quad \begin{align*}

\implies a  &= \dfrac {-24}{3} \\
\implies a  &= -8
\end{align*}

